    <section class="section" id="problem">
      <div class="container">
        <span class="eyebrow">The Problem</span>
        <h2 class="section-title">Modern homes are incredibly capable and incredibly fragile.</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">
          Most households operate on the assumption that core systems will always be available: electricity, municipal water, cellular networks, cloud accounts, digital records, stocked stores, and frictionless deliveries. When those systems work, modern life feels effortless. When they fail, even briefly, most families discover they do not have a real operating plan.
        </p>

        <div class="grid-3">
          <article class="card">
            <h3>Infrastructure Dependence</h3>
            <p>
              A modern household depends on outside systems for power, water, communications, food access, and records verification. A short disruption can quickly become an operational problem.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>Hidden Weak Links</h3>
            <p>
              Most homes have supplies. Fewer have systems. Weak links usually hide in boring places: medication runway, backup power assumptions, sanitation, records access, household procedures, and device charging.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>Improvised Response</h3>
            <p>
              In many households, emergency planning consists of “we’ll figure it out.” Under stress, improvisation is rarely as effective as people imagine. Households need structure before the event, not during it.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="method">
      <div class="container">
        <span class="eyebrow">The Method</span>
        <h2 class="section-title">A structured framework for household continuity.</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">
          EPICS Consulting is built on the EPICS Dash-1 framework: <strong>Emergency Procedures for the Suburban Jungle.</strong> Dash-1 provides the doctrine, procedures, and system architecture. Consulting provides implementation, prioritization, and real-world household planning.
        </p>

        <div class="grid-3">
          <article class="card method-card">
            <h3>Assess</h3>
            <p>
              We evaluate the household across energy, water, food, medical, communications, records, sanitation, and continuity factors. The goal is to identify practical failure points before they become real problems.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="card method-card">
            <h3>Prioritize</h3>
            <p>
              Not every weakness matters equally. Recommendations are sequenced by operational value, cost efficiency, and actual household dependency, not internet drama.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="card method-card">
            <h3>Implement</h3>
            <p>
              The outcome is not a pile of gear. It is a household system: capabilities, staging, procedures, documentation, and clear next steps for each person in the home.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>

        <div class="grid-4" style="margin-top: 1.1rem;">
          <article class="card">
            <h4>Energy</h4>
            <p>Power continuity, load planning, backup power hierarchy, charging strategy, and fuel assumptions.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card">
            <h4>Water</h4>
            <p>Storage runway, alternate sourcing, purification capability, distribution, and household use planning.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card">
            <h4>Medical</h4>
            <p>Prescription runway, critical dependencies, skills, staged equipment, and household-specific medical risk.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card">
            <h4>Records</h4>
            <p>Digital, legal, and physical continuity for identity, insurance, property, medical, and financial access.</p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

